Radiological gastrostomy - monthly variation

Martin Hennessy

25/05/2021

  • Included are data about 793 gastrostomies performed on 754 patients between 2014-01-06 and 2021-05-06
  • Repeat gastrostomies are counted only if the new gastrostomy required a new gastric puncture
  • Re-canalisation of existing tracts with a wire are not included

Number of gastrostomies performed in a given month

  • Between 1 and 18 have been performed in the previous 89 months

  • These data can be displayed as a histogram:

  • The data look quite evenly distributed but this can be tested with the Shapiro-Wilk test of normality.

  • With the null hypothesis being even distribution, p = 0.022003

  • Median = 8 (IQR 6-11)

  • These can also be displayed as a boxplot:

30-day mortality in a given month

  • The frequency of the number of times 30-day mortality occurs in a month can be show as a histogram:

  • To test these numbers of deaths are within the expectation of random variation, we can use Poisson probability statistics.

  • A Poisson probability test expresses the probability of a given number of events (30-day mortality) occurring in a fixed time interval (one month), assuming new events are independent of events in the previous time interval (the previous months deaths do not influence the probability of the following months deaths), based only on a known mean rate (0.4719101).

  • The table below presents observed 30-day mortality numbers and those expected by Poisson probablity:

Patients dead at 30 days Observed frequency Expected frequency
0 58 56
1 22 26
2 7 6
3 2 1
  • Chi squared test with the null hypothesis that there is no difference between observed and expected frequencies: p = 1
